Steve Gardner writes:
> Michael Norrish wrote:

>> If it really is that important that people should vote on Proposals,
>> then we shouldn't charge people for the privilege.  It seems to me
>> that the basic thrust of the Duty to Vote proposal is to return Agora
>> to the way it used to be, when voting was much more universal.  
 
> Yes and no. It is true that what I'm trying to achieve with 'A Duty
> to Vote' is increased voter turnout. But this does not represent a
> return to the way things used to be because the rest of the game has
> changed so much since the days when voting was free. Let me
> emphasize once again that I'm coming at this from a game designer's
> perspective. The question I'm asking voters to ask themselves is:
> will 'A Duty to Vote' make the game interesting? I think the answer
> is 'yes'.
 
I think that in both stopping people from saving (with your suggestion
to lower the VTCL), and in forcing them to spend on voting, you are
removing, or at least making more difficult, a possible strategy for
game-play, and I think that's bad.  The strategy in question is one
I've been attempting to play myself, and that is to accumulate VTs as
an insurance policy against Indulgence problems and to be able perhaps
to swing votes on crucial proposals.  Actually, I wouldn't be
surprised if my voting behaviour was actually compatible with 'A Duty
to Vote', but I've also been pretty well paid thanks to having held
three salaried offices until recently.  Others might not find it so
easy to pursue this strategy if 'A Duty to Vote' passed.

> The trouble is, nobody else seems to have any other ideas. To tell
> you the truth, it's a bit depressing to encounter so much resistance
> to new ideas when they're the only ideas anyone is putting
> forward. Is any of this relentless negativism going to be balanced
> by a constructive alternative? I'm proposing a 3 month trial of a
> different way of doing things. I'm prepared to try something
> different and see what happens.  And if we don't like it, it will go
> away. What are you proposing?
 
How about this (an idea had over the weekend): 

Allow a proposal to be made free-to-vote by having people pay the
Promotor (in VTs) in advance of its distribution.  You could make this
cost as much as the number of Players multiplied by the current Voting
Tariff, but I think it would be more encouraging to give someone being
so charitable a discount of perhaps 50%.

All Players could vote once on a free-to-vote proposal without charge,
so that the Assessor would only bill people for second votes, (and
groups if they voted at all).

Another twist (though probably more complicated without real reward)
might be to allow for the funding of a limited number of votes, and
then that many votes on the proposal would be free, but subsequent
votes would be charged.  I don't much like this, but it might appeal
to the particularly frugal. 

The model I have in mind is that the proposor of a proposal would pay
not only a P-Note to get it distributed, but would also make a
free-for-vote payment.  This is better than just distributing VTs to 
Players as it is better targetted and does not require lots of
miniature contracts to be repeatedly negotiated, but worse in that
there is no guarantee that people will vote in a particular way. 

Michael.

