Scott Goehring wrote:
>
>"Steve" == Steve Gardner <gardner@silas-1.cc.monash.edu.au> writes:
>
>Steve> Fix *what* correctly? Or get rid of *what*?
>
>The economy, or at least the sorry excuse we have for one.

What I'd say we have is a not completely well-designed game.
Nevertheless, there are a number of good ideas in the current design
which I think are worth further elaboration. 

Do you have any ideas to fix the economy, or is your preferred option
to "do away with it entirely", whatever that might mean?

>Steve> The problem as I see it is that more P-Notes are going in than
>Steve> out of circulation.
>
>The problem is that all aspects of the economy are arbitrary and
>fixed.  

What does that mean, precisely? All aspects of every game are arbitrary.
For that matter, the whole universe might be arbitrary - we don't have a
satisfactory answer to the question: why is there something rather than
nothing?

But from a perspective internal to the game, the elements of the economy
do not seem to me to be arbitrary. If Nomic is essentially anything (a
dubious claim perhaps), then it is essentially a game of making
proposals and voting on them (although Fascist comes to mind as a
counterexample). So the existence of VTs and P-Notes is internally
justified and so not arbitrary. That doesn't mean we couldn't get rid of
them and try something completely different - of course we could. But
these are the ideas we're exploring at the moment.

What do you mean by 'fixed'?

>Your endless tinkering with inflows and outflows (which will, of
>course, never solve the problem, just shuffle it around into mazes of
>ever-growing complexity) will never fix that.

But I'm not really 'tinkering' with inflows and outflows, at least at
the moment. What I understand by 'tinkering' is changing individual
Rules so that certain actions give greater or lesser rewards or
penalties of economic items. For example, amending the Zeitgeist Rule
(1047) so that Zeitgeists get only 1 P-Note rather than 3 was tinkering.
Most of the tinkering of that kind that needs to be done has been done.
But the creations of R1852 (Ciruclation of Voting Tokens) and R1854 (The
Chancellor can set the BOS) are not tinkering, but significant
conceptual developments. I'm not saying that these Rules will forever be
enshrined as features of our game, but I think they are sufficiently
interesting ideas to be worth playing around with for a while yet.


