Charles E. Carroll wrote:
>
>Scott Goehring wrote:
>>
>>Steve> The problem as I see it is that more P-Notes are going in than
>>Steve> out of circulation.
>>
>>The problem is that all aspects of the economy are arbitrary and
>>fixed.  Your endless tinkering with inflows and outflows (which will,
>>of course, never solve the problem, just shuffle it around into mazes
>>of ever-growing complexity) will never fix that.
>
>I think I agree with Scott, at least in this instance.  The operation
>of the Proposal Queue should provide a natural competition among
>Proposals leading to an expenditure of P-Notes related to the
>P-Notes in circulation.  Particularly with a small batch size.
>I think with the current system, as long as there is a competition
>between Proposals to get distributed, it doesn't matter much if
>there's a few dozen P-Notes in circulation or a few thousand--the
>economy should naturally reach a balance.
>
>If we don't have a balance now, it's because there *isn't* competition
>between Proposals to be distributed.  I can't speak for anyone else,
>but I know I haven't been making Proposals lately simply due to a lack of
>time--not due to any in-game factors.  If this is the case among
>many of the Players, I don't know if anything can fix it--but
>I certainly don't think that further reducing the P-Note supply
>will encourage more Proposals.

It had never occurred to me that reducing P-Note supply would encourage
more Proposals, any more than reducing VT supply was supposed to
encourage people to vote. The purpose of reducing supply is to prevent
the value of economic items being reduced by inflation.

Of course, if nobody has any interest in making Proposals, then the
value of P-Notes is going to be close to zero whatever the situation is
with respect to P-Note supply. The concept of P-Notes is premised on
there being Players who wish to make Proposals. At the moment, that
doesn't seem to be the case - and this is a problem which we need to
address. But 'The P-Note Tap' is not designed to address it. 


